.SH NAME
Net::Nostr::Event \- Nostr protocol event object
.SH SYNOPSIS
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.Vb 2
\&    use Net::Nostr::Event;
\&    use Net::Nostr::Key;
\&
\&    # Typical usage: create via Key (sets pubkey and signs automatically)
\&    my $key   = Net::Nostr::Key\->new;
\&    my $event = $key\->create_event(kind => 1, content => \*(Aqhello\*(Aq, tags => []);
\&    say $event\->id;   # 64\-char hex sha256
\&    say $event\->sig;  # 128\-char hex signature
\&
\&    # Manual construction (local builder \-\- defaults created_at, tags, id)
\&    my $event = Net::Nostr::Event\->new(
\&        pubkey     => $key\->pubkey_hex,
\&        kind       => 1,
\&        content    => \*(Aqhello world\*(Aq,
\&        tags       => [[\*(Aqt\*(Aq, \*(Aqnostr\*(Aq]],
\&        created_at => 1700000000,
\&    );
\&
\&    # Parse from wire (strict \-\- all 7 fields required, no defaults)
\&    my $event = Net::Nostr::Event\->from_wire(\e%hash);
\&
\&    say $event\->json_serialize;  # canonical JSON array for hashing
\&    my $hash = $event\->to_hash;  # { id, pubkey, created_at, kind, tags, content, sig }
.Ve
.SH DESCRIPTION
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
Represents a Nostr event as defined by NIP\-01. Handles canonical JSON
serialization, automatic ID computation, kind classification, and
signature verification.
.PP
Events are \fBimmutable after construction\fR. The body fields (\f(CW\*(C`id\*(C'\fR,
\&\f(CW\*(C`pubkey\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`created_at\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`kind\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`tags\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`content\*(C'\fR) are read\-only.
The only writable field is \f(CW\*(C`sig\*(C'\fR, which does not participate in the
event ID computation. Tags are deep\-copied on input and output so that
callers cannot invalidate an event through retained references. This
prevents a class of bugs where mutating a field silently invalidates the
event ID and any existing signature.
.SH CONSTRUCTOR
.IX Header "CONSTRUCTOR"
.SS new
.IX Subsection "new"
.Vb 8
\&    my $event = Net::Nostr::Event\->new(
\&        pubkey     => $hex_pubkey,
\&        kind       => 1,
\&        content    => \*(Aqhello\*(Aq,
\&        tags       => [[\*(Aqp\*(Aq, $pubkey]],
\&        created_at => time(),
\&        sig        => $hex_sig,
\&    );
.Ve
.PP
Strict builder for local event construction. \f(CW\*(C`pubkey\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`kind\*(C'\fR, and
\&\f(CW\*(C`content\*(C'\fR are required. \f(CW\*(C`tags\*(C'\fR defaults to \f(CW\*(C`[]\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`created_at\*(C'\fR defaults
to \f(CWtime()\fR, and \f(CW\*(C`id\*(C'\fR is automatically computed from the canonical
serialization. If \f(CW\*(C`id\*(C'\fR is passed explicitly, it is preserved as\-is.
.PP
For events parsed from the wire, use "from_wire" instead, which requires
all seven NIP\-01 fields and does not apply any defaults.
.PP
Croaks if any required field is missing or if values fail format validation:
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`pubkey\*(C'\fR must be 64\-character lowercase hex
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`kind\*(C'\fR must be an integer between 0 and 65535
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`content\*(C'\fR must be defined
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`sig\*(C'\fR, if provided, must be 128\-character lowercase hex
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`id\*(C'\fR, if provided, must be 64\-character lowercase hex
.IP \(bu 4
Unknown arguments are rejected
.SS from_wire
.IX Subsection "from_wire"
.Vb 1
\&    my $event = Net::Nostr::Event\->from_wire(\e%hash);
.Ve
.PP
Strict wire parser. Constructs an event from a hashref received over the
wire (e.g. from JSON\-decoded protocol messages). All seven NIP\-01 event
fields are required: \f(CW\*(C`id\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`pubkey\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`created_at\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`kind\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`tags\*(C'\fR,
\&\f(CW\*(C`content\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`sig\*(C'\fR. No defaults are applied. Croaks if any field is
missing, undefined, or fails format validation.
.PP
This is the entry point used by "parse" in Net::Nostr::Message for EVENT
and AUTH messages. Use "new" for local event construction where
defaults (\f(CW\*(C`created_at\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`tags\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`id\*(C'\fR) are convenient.
.PP
.Vb 3
\&    my $hash = { id => \*(Aq...\*(Aq, pubkey => \*(Aq...\*(Aq, created_at => 1000,
\&                 kind => 1, tags => [], content => \*(Aqhi\*(Aq, sig => \*(Aq...\*(Aq };
\&    my $event = Net::Nostr::Event\->from_wire($hash);
.Ve
.SH ACCESSORS
.IX Header "ACCESSORS"
All body accessors are \fBread\-only\fR. Attempting to set them after
construction will croak. \f(CW\*(C`sig\*(C'\fR is the only writable accessor.
.SS id
.IX Subsection "id"
.Vb 1
\&    my $id = $event\->id;  # \*(Aq3bf0c63f...\*(Aq (64\-char hex)
.Ve
.PP
Returns the event ID, a SHA\-256 hex digest of the canonical serialization.
Read\-only.
.SS pubkey
.IX Subsection "pubkey"
.Vb 1
\&    my $pubkey = $event\->pubkey;
.Ve
.PP
Returns the author\*(Aqs public key as a 64\-character hex string. Read\-only.
.SS created_at
.IX Subsection "created_at"
.Vb 1
\&    my $ts = $event\->created_at;  # Unix timestamp
.Ve
.PP
Returns the event creation timestamp. Read\-only.
.SS kind
.IX Subsection "kind"
.Vb 1
\&    my $kind = $event\->kind;  # 1
.Ve
.PP
Returns the event kind (integer). Read\-only.
.SS tags
.IX Subsection "tags"
.Vb 1
\&    my $tags = $event\->tags;  # [[\*(Aqp\*(Aq, \*(Aqabc...\*(Aq], [\*(Aqe\*(Aq, \*(Aqdef...\*(Aq]]
.Ve
.PP
Returns a deep copy of the tags arrayref. Each tag is an arrayref of
strings. Read\-only. All tags must be provided at construction time.
.PP
Tags are deep\-copied both on input (during construction) and on output
(from this accessor and "to_hash"), so callers cannot accidentally
mutate the event\*(Aqs internal state through retained references.
.SS content
.IX Subsection "content"
.Vb 1
\&    my $content = $event\->content;
.Ve
.PP
Returns the event content string. Read\-only.
.SS sig
.IX Subsection "sig"
.Vb 2
\&    my $sig = $event\->sig;           # get
\&    $event\->sig($hex_signature);     # set
.Ve
.PP
Gets or sets the Schnorr signature as a 128\-character lowercase hex string.
This is the only writable field because the signature does not participate
in event ID computation. Setting \f(CW\*(C`undef\*(C'\fR clears the signature. The setter
croaks if the value is defined but not valid 128\-char lowercase hex.
.SS json_serialize
.IX Subsection "json_serialize"
.Vb 1
\&    my $json = $event\->json_serialize;
.Ve
.PP
Returns the canonical JSON serialization used for ID computation:
\&\f(CW\*(C`[0, pubkey, created_at, kind, tags, content]\*(C'\fR. The output is UTF\-8
encoded with no extra whitespace.
.SS to_hash
.IX Subsection "to_hash"
.Vb 3
\&    my $hash = $event\->to_hash;
\&    # { id => \*(Aq...\*(Aq, pubkey => \*(Aq...\*(Aq, created_at => 1000,
\&    #   kind => 1, tags => [...], content => \*(Aq...\*(Aq, sig => \*(Aq...\*(Aq }
.Ve
.PP
Returns a hashref with all seven event fields. The \f(CW\*(C`tags\*(C'\fR value is a
deep copy, so mutating it will not affect the event. Useful for JSON
encoding the full event object.
.SH METHODS
.IX Header "METHODS"
.SS difficulty
.IX Subsection "difficulty"
.Vb 1
\&    my $bits = $event\->difficulty;  # e.g. 21
.Ve
.PP
Returns the Proof of Work difficulty of the event, defined as the number of
leading zero bits in the event ID (NIP\-13). For example, an ID starting with
\&\f(CW\*(C`000006d8\*(C'\fR has 21 leading zero bits.
.PP
.Vb 3
\&    my $event = $key\->create_event(kind => 1, content => \*(Aqhello\*(Aq, tags => []);
\&    my $mined = $event\->mine(16);
\&    say $mined\->difficulty;  # >= 16
.Ve
.SS committed_target_difficulty
.IX Subsection "committed_target_difficulty"
.Vb 1
\&    my $target = $event\->committed_target_difficulty;  # e.g. 20, or undef
.Ve
.PP
Returns the committed target difficulty from the \f(CW\*(C`nonce\*(C'\fR tag\*(Aqs third entry
(NIP\-13), or \f(CW\*(C`undef\*(C'\fR if no nonce tag or no target is present. This allows
clients and relays to reject events where the miner committed to a lower
difficulty than required, even if the actual difficulty happens to be higher.
.PP
.Vb 2
\&    my $mined = $event\->mine(20);
\&    say $mined\->committed_target_difficulty;  # 20
.Ve
.SS mine
.IX Subsection "mine"
.Vb 1
\&    my $mined = $event\->mine($target_difficulty);
.Ve
.PP
Returns a new Net::Nostr::Event with a \f(CW\*(C`nonce\*(C'\fR tag that gives the event
at least \f(CW$target_difficulty\fR leading zero bits in its ID (NIP\-13). The
original event is not modified. The nonce tag\*(Aqs third entry records the
committed target difficulty.
.PP
The returned event is unsigned \-\- call \f(CW\*(C`$key\->sign_event($mined)\*(C'\fR to
sign it after mining.
.PP
.Vb 4
\&    my $event = $key\->create_event(kind => 1, content => \*(Aqhello\*(Aq, tags => []);
\&    my $mined = $event\->mine(20);
\&    $key\->sign_event($mined);
\&    say $mined\->difficulty;  # >= 20
.Ve
.PP
Existing tags are preserved. If the event already has a \f(CW\*(C`nonce\*(C'\fR tag, it is
replaced. The \f(CW\*(C`created_at\*(C'\fR timestamp is updated during mining.
.PP
Since the NIP\-01 event ID does not commit to the signature, mining can be
delegated to a third party (delegated Proof of Work).
.SS d_tag
.IX Subsection "d_tag"
.Vb 1
\&    my $d = $event\->d_tag;  # \*(Aq\*(Aq if no d tag
.Ve
.PP
Returns the value of the first \f(CW\*(C`d\*(C'\fR tag, or empty string if none exists.
Used for addressable event deduplication (kinds 30000\-39999).
.PP
.Vb 5
\&    my $event = Net::Nostr::Event\->new(
\&        pubkey => \*(Aqa\*(Aq x 64, kind => 30023,
\&        content => \*(Aq\*(Aq, tags => [[\*(Aqd\*(Aq, \*(Aqmy\-article\*(Aq]],
\&    );
\&    say $event\->d_tag;  # \*(Aqmy\-article\*(Aq
.Ve
.SS expiration
.IX Subsection "expiration"
.Vb 1
\&    my $ts = $event\->expiration;  # Unix timestamp, or undef
.Ve
.PP
Returns the value of the \f(CW\*(C`expiration\*(C'\fR tag (NIP\-40) as a number, or \f(CW\*(C`undef\*(C'\fR
if the event has no expiration tag.
.PP
.Vb 5
\&    my $event = Net::Nostr::Event\->new(
\&        pubkey => \*(Aqa\*(Aq x 64, kind => 1, content => \*(Aqtemp\*(Aq,
\&        tags => [[\*(Aqexpiration\*(Aq, \*(Aq1600000000\*(Aq]],
\&    );
\&    say $event\->expiration;  # 1600000000
.Ve
.SS is_expired
.IX Subsection "is_expired"
.Vb 2
\&    my $bool = $event\->is_expired;
\&    my $bool = $event\->is_expired($now);
.Ve
.PP
Returns true if the event has an \f(CW\*(C`expiration\*(C'\fR tag (NIP\-40) and the
expiration time has passed. Accepts an optional Unix timestamp to compare
against (defaults to \f(CWtime()\fR). Returns false if there is no expiration
tag.
.PP
.Vb 3
\&    if ($event\->is_expired) {
\&        # ignore or discard the event
\&    }
.Ve
.SS content_warning
.IX Subsection "content_warning"
.Vb 1
\&    my $reason = $event\->content_warning;  # string, \*(Aq\*(Aq or undef
.Ve
.PP
Returns the value of the \f(CW\*(C`content\-warning\*(C'\fR tag (NIP\-36), or \f(CW\*(C`undef\*(C'\fR if
the event has no content warning tag. Returns an empty string if the tag
is present but has no reason.
.PP
.Vb 5
\&    my $event = Net::Nostr::Event\->new(
\&        pubkey => \*(Aqa\*(Aq x 64, kind => 1, content => \*(Aqsensitive\*(Aq,
\&        tags => [[\*(Aqcontent\-warning\*(Aq, \*(Aqspoiler\*(Aq]],
\&    );
\&    say $event\->content_warning;  # \*(Aqspoiler\*(Aq
.Ve
.SS has_content_warning
.IX Subsection "has_content_warning"
.Vb 1
\&    my $bool = $event\->has_content_warning;
.Ve
.PP
Returns true if the event has a \f(CW\*(C`content\-warning\*(C'\fR tag (NIP\-36). Clients
can use this to hide content until the user opts in.
.PP
.Vb 3
\&    if ($event\->has_content_warning) {
\&        # hide content behind a warning
\&    }
.Ve
.SS content_warning_tag
.IX Subsection "content_warning_tag"
.Vb 2
\&    my $tag = Net::Nostr::Event\->content_warning_tag(\*(Aqspoiler\*(Aq);
\&    my $tag = Net::Nostr::Event\->content_warning_tag();
.Ve
.PP
Class method that creates a \f(CW\*(C`content\-warning\*(C'\fR tag arrayref, suitable for
inclusion in an event\*(Aqs tags. The reason is optional.
.PP
.Vb 6
\&    my $event = Net::Nostr::Event\->new(
\&        pubkey  => \*(Aqa\*(Aq x 64,
\&        kind    => 1,
\&        content => \*(Aqspoiler content\*(Aq,
\&        tags    => [Net::Nostr::Event\->content_warning_tag(\*(Aqspoiler\*(Aq)],
\&    );
.Ve
.SS is_regular
.IX Subsection "is_regular"
.Vb 1
\&    $event\->is_regular;  # true for kinds 1, 2, 4\-44, 1000\-9999
.Ve
.PP
Returns true if the event kind is a regular (non\-replaceable, non\-ephemeral,
non\-addressable) kind.
.SS is_replaceable
.IX Subsection "is_replaceable"
.Vb 1
\&    $event\->is_replaceable;  # true for kinds 0, 3, 10000\-19999
.Ve
.PP
Returns true if the event kind is replaceable (only latest per pubkey+kind
is kept).
.SS is_ephemeral
.IX Subsection "is_ephemeral"
.Vb 1
\&    $event\->is_ephemeral;  # true for kinds 20000\-29999
.Ve
.PP
Returns true if the event kind is ephemeral (broadcast but never stored).
.SS is_addressable
.IX Subsection "is_addressable"
.Vb 1
\&    $event\->is_addressable;  # true for kinds 30000\-39999
.Ve
.PP
Returns true if the event kind is addressable (only latest per
pubkey+kind+d_tag is kept).
.SS is_protected
.IX Subsection "is_protected"
.Vb 1
\&    $event\->is_protected;  # true if ["\-"] tag is present
.Ve
.PP
Returns true if the event contains a \f(CW\*(C`["\-"]\*(C'\fR tag (NIP\-70). Protected
events can only be published to relays by their author. Relays MUST
reject protected events unless the client has authenticated (NIP\-42) as
the event\*(Aqs pubkey.
.SS validate
.IX Subsection "validate"
.Vb 1
\&    $event\->validate;  # croaks on failure, returns 1 on success
.Ve
.PP
Full cryptographic validation: recomputes the event ID from the canonical
serialization, compares it to the stored \f(CW\*(C`id\*(C'\fR, and verifies the Schnorr
signature against the event\*(Aqs own \f(CW\*(C`pubkey\*(C'\fR. Croaks if the event is
unsigned, the ID does not match, or the signature is invalid.
.PP
This is the method callers should use to verify events received from
untrusted sources (relays, peers, files).
.PP
.Vb 2
\&    my $event = Net::Nostr::Message\->parse($json)\->event;
\&    $event\->validate;  # croaks if tampered or forged
.Ve
.SS verify_sig
.IX Subsection "verify_sig"
.Vb 1
\&    my $valid = $event\->verify_sig($key);
.Ve
.PP
Low\-level signature check: verifies the Schnorr signature against the
stored \f(CW\*(C`id\*(C'\fR using the given Net::Nostr::Key object. Croaks if the
key\*(Aqs pubkey does not match \f(CW\*(C`$event\->pubkey\*(C'\fR. Does \fBnot\fR recompute
the event ID \-\- use "validate" for full verification.
.PP
.Vb 3
\&    my $key   = Net::Nostr::Key\->new;
\&    my $event = $key\->create_event(kind => 1, content => \*(Aqsigned\*(Aq, tags => []);
\&    say $event\->verify_sig($key);  # 1
.Ve
